body.plain: Miranda Lambert was born November 10, 1983 in Longview, Texas to Richard Lee and Beverly June Hughes Lambert.  She has a brother, Luke.  The 5'4" country music artist/songwriter gained fame as a finalist on the 2003 season of Nashville Star, where she finished in third place and later signed to Epic Records.  Miranda married Blake Shelton on May 14, 2011 but the couple divorced on July 20, 2015. Lambert is especially known for “The House that Built Me”, “White Liar” and “Kerosene”.

The 32-year-old is undoubtedly in a much darker place than she was in the angry, spitfire days of “Kerosene” and “Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.”

description.plain:
A “grass is always greener” perspective on one of the main characters from L. Frank Baum’s The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, who wanted nothing more than a heart to feel emotions.

The singer, the recent victim of a broken heart, warns him how painful emotions can be and offers to trade places with the Tin Man, giving him her damaged heart in exchange for the protection of his metallic body.

description.plain:
“Little Red Wagon” was released as the third single from Miranda Lambert’s fifth studio album, Platinum.  It was originally performed by Audra Mae on her 2012 album, Audra Mae & The Almighty Sound.

The songs lyrics riff on the Willie Nelson classic, “Won’t You Ride In My Little Red Wagon.”

How did Lambert first hear the song? She explains at Great American Country:

John Eddie is an artist who has come out on the road with us before and opened a few times. He called my tour manager three or four years ago and said, ‘Hey, tell Miranda about this girl Audra Mae, specifically her song ‘Little Red Wagon.’ I think she could rock it.



Lambert performed the song at the 2015 Grammy Awards. She’s also recorded an official music video.

description.plain: Miranda and Blake wrote this son about Blake’s brother who was killed in a car accident at the age of 24. Blake was 14 at the time. It was in December, but the song references the fact that it is still hard to deal with his death no matter that it isn’t the anniversary or anything. His parent’s gave Blake all of his brother’s music and Blake would listen to the records over and over remembering his brother and feeling him there. I know you didn’t mean to give them to me is because it was an accident and it makes Blake mad that he’s gone, that he doesn’t get to see him any more. How dare you leave me? His Dad is referenced in an interview saying It isn’t something you ever get over, you just get used to it.

description.plain:
“Highway Vagabond” is a song about the virtues of being a drifter.  While it certainly applies to the life of a traveling musician, it really speaks to all  those with a restless spirit.

The opening lines also encourage the listener to follow the beat of their own drum:  “I wanna go somewhere nobody knows. I wanna know somewhere nobody goes”, essentially telling us to follow our own dream, not those pushed on us by conventional thinkers.

description.plain: This song makes sense, once you adjust your thinking about gender.  The voice is female, but it’s the story of the man who’s involved with her.  It makes you wonder why he isn’t here to tell the story himself, and that makes for some tantalizing speculation.
